segments.text: opposed to drinking.
I had heard that he was a strong prohibitionist.
Does that partly link back to his Baptist roots, you think?
Well, probably maybe.
I don't know about that.
Was that a lifetime attitude for him?
Yes.
We never, ever had anything in our home.
And he was so against the young people.
And at A&M, it was, you got in real bad trouble if you were caught.
All right, let's go back to, what were the important buildings at A&M when you all arrived?
Well, you know, I have the vague idea

recollection of that administration building it was a big old-fashioned now this is the new one or the one that this is not the one that burned this is the new one well it wouldn't be the new one maybe it was the one that burned i don't know about when one burned all right i'm thinking that you know they see the whole campus is different from what it was because there's a railroad station still that
They tore it down about 10 years ago.
They tore it down.
You see, everything that came to the campus came on the, I keep wanting to say Southern Pacific.
I'm not sure which branch it was.
Southern Pacific and Burlington Rock Island both ran on that.
They came on that track.
And that's the way you got.
You got off the train, and there were iron gates, as I remember, across that.
And you know, this is all on the west side of what's there now.
And you just came in those gates.
And then there were this oval street.
One went up this way and one this way.
And the administration building, as I recall, was right here at the top of the oval.
And then there were houses that came down this way, and the other side didn't have houses.
But our house and the Kyle house and the Fountain house, there were different houses down the side there.
And that was...
Were there any trees of any size on the campus then?
Yeah, seems like there were.
But that train created quite a problem, because the students would go to Bryan.
They said they had freight trains that came in there, too.
And so the boys had a habit of hanging on the train or jumping
holding on, then when they got the five miles out to college, they'd jump off.
And one terrible time, I don't know whether this is of any interest, but this one student jumped off of the train, and it was terribly, really against the rules.
They were not supposed to do that.
And he jumped off.
And it caught his arm some way and pulled it off.
And he picked that arm up and walked up to the infirmary.
Now, where the infirmary was back in those days was kind of angled off from the house where we lived.
And my father did.
But you wouldn't have any recollection of that because the whole school's different from now.
But there was a convenience for my father to go.
But he went over there every afternoon to check on the students that were sick.
And they called him that night about this.
And he got up and went over there.
And I don't know the outcome of that.
I'm sure they could then get it back on.
I don't know.
But things like that, that's the reason they didn't want them jumping on that train like that.
During your years there, do you remember any other calamities?
Were there any big fires or tornadoes?
Well, I guess about the main thing,

thing that i can remember is the flu epidemic that was really about really a bad one please describe that for us well i don't i can't really describe it except every day there'd be more students going getting into the the um and i guess they called it infirmary and
And I don't remember.
I think maybe there might have been a few deaths, but I'm not sure about that.
Was the infirmary able to serve all of them, or did they have to send some of them back to the dormitories?
Well, I don't remember about that, but I know they were really crowded and worried my father terribly.
Let's see.
You took A&M classes.
Please describe some of the teachers that you remember, some of the good faculty members.
Did you have English from Tommy Mayo, for example?
No, I don't believe so.
I can't remember many of the teachers.
Well, those classes, were they easy?
Were they rigorous?
Well, they were hard for me because I always felt like the courses at A&M would be harder than any place else anyway.
I don't know why.
But I took what I thought were such hard courses.
And I got along.
I got along okay with them.
But chemistry was...
Not ever one of my favorite subjects.
That was kind of hard for me.
That was one, was that one of your harder courses?
Well, it was for me.
I always did like math.
Not that it would ever do me any good, but it was like a game, you know, algebra and... Did, as far back as I know,
There were many, many nicknames for faculty members and others.
Were there nicknames then?
Oh, there were nicknames for the students.
I was going through this old book, and several of my friends were in there.
And I noticed this one very handsome, married Lily Best Kyle, named Harry Baker.
And his name was Trash.
Everybody on the campus called him Trash.
And the one I was dating with was his best friend.
And his name was just plain old T. Lewis.
They never did have a nickname for him.
But we used to say.
T. Lewis and Trash would come by and get Lilybeth and me, and we'd go dating.
And, of course, the head yell leader was Catfish Goodman.
Everybody knew Catfish Goodman.
Were they called yell leaders then?
Why, certainly.
You don't think they'd be called cheerleaders, do you?
Well, I was wondering.
Well, I should say not.
That's like Texas University.
That's right, that's right.
No, we used to make more fun of, you know, cheerleaders, and that was just a bad word.
And then the way the...
the way the band leader went with all the prancing.
They all do that.
Bands do that.
Was the band very much respected then?
Oh, you bet.
And it sure is now.
My son lives in Enid for several years.
His good friend
was in the press box at the Mall Games.
And he wanted Lee to help him with spotting the team, so Lee was in the press box with him.
And they've always kidding me about Texas A&M, because I made such a silly thing out of it for myself.

the A&M oh I tell you what about this I'll switch up back to something when I was in Texas University the that was the year that my father was invited to come to OU and so he called me one day and he said I've been invited to come
to be president of Oklahoma University.
And he said, I'm talking to the family about it.
He said, now, what would you think about it if I should take that position?
And of course, I said just what anybody would have said.
If that's what you want to do, then that's what you must do.
I think that was a compliment to you.
And I should say it.
that just think it over good.
And then I said, there's just one thing.
If you take that job at the OU, don't you ever allow OU and A&M to play football.
That was our conversation about that.
And sure enough, now they play all the time.
And that is just terrible for me.
You're torn.
Yeah.
Well, I'm not too torn.
But when I went to Texas, that was kind of a tough thing for me, too.
I tried to make all the dances at OU.
But the train went to Bryan.
I mean, to Hearn.
Remember, is Hearn still there?
Yes, ma'am.

They'd meet me up there at Hearn, and I'd get off the train and spend the weekend and go to the core dance on Saturday night and go back to... And in spite of all that, I had some friends down at Texas A&M.
I joined a sorority.
I was a pi-fi down there.
And...
So there was a lot that was very nice about it, but it never, ever came anywhere close to taking any feeling that I didn't have for A&M.
That was just, that was just, the spirit they talk about all the time really got into me.
Don't you want some more pillows behind you?
Well, thank you, Carolyn.
I think you need propping up.
Yeah.
Well, I'm doing a lot of talking, but it's not anything that's going to help Dr. Martin.
Is that better?
Yeah, that's fine.
Thank you.
Make believe that I had never heard about this spirit.
What was this Aggie spirit?
I don't know, but it got into people mighty good.
How?
What caused people to be proud of it?
Oh, I guess it was just everything was so close together and all just, all cadets and
And not too much diversion.
I don't know.
I don't know what you call it.
Were there some events that brought people together?
That I recall.
Did y'all have yell practices then?
Yeah, sure.
Where were they held?
Well, sometimes they would come around.
The whole student body would come and gather around the
front porch at our house.
And the father would come out there and he'd give them pep talk and they'd all cheer and yell and that kind of spirit.
Did they ever attempt to play any tricks on your father, any pranks anywhere around the house?
The students?
Yes, ma'am.
Well, I think that, I don't recall right now.
You don't remember any trash on the front porch?
No, nothing like that.
They always seemed like they were very respectful.
When you attended class, what did a young lady wear to class in those days?
Oh, something just...
tailored plain kind of clothes.
You remind me, your answer reminds me of what Mrs. Walton told me she wore, so then to try to provoke your thoughts, you had faded blue jeans, sneakers.
I can guarantee that I didn't wear anything like that.
Would it have been a dress or a two-piece outfit?
Oh, it would be a dress.
What length?
What skirt length?
What was the hemline?
Well, it was just a modest hemline.
I don't know exactly because the hems change so much.
And what kind of makeup would a coed have worn?
Just about like what they're wearing now, if they don't put too much.
And how long would a young lady's hair have been?
You know, I was looking at some of the pictures of what they call senior favorites.
What are you all showing around?
Well, he just mentioned hemlines and hairdos.
So it was okay for a young lady to cut her hair then?

Oh, well, it was quite a big deal in my family about my hair because the girls were cutting the hair, and mine never did go real long, but it came down to about shoulder blade length, and I wanted to cut it, and my parents wouldn't let me.
for a long time.
And so on some birthday that I was having, my father was out of town.
And I got a telegram from him.
He said, you have my permission to cut your hair.
So my mother made the appointment.
And Carolyn, I think maybe it's a little cool in here.
She made an appointment at this beauty shop down there and took me to Houston and had my hair cut and I still have the hair upstairs.
They took my hair and just made it into a
kind of a roll sort of thing, about this long.
And that was the time when they made hairnets out of real hair.
And they wanted to give my mother $25 for my hair, and she wouldn't take it.
So it's still upstairs.
But anyway, that's how, when I got my hair cut.
I think I was 16, 17.
This photo here.
Oh, look.
Is that in front of the president's house?
Yeah.
I remember that day we had that taken.
I don't remember the day, but I remember.
What was the occasion?
Was that a birthday?
No, I don't think so.
Whose straw hat is that right there by the rocking chair?
I don't have any idea.
Is that yours?
Well, I'm having a little trouble seeing it.
Where is the hat?
Right back there.
Oh, down here.
I don't know.
Would a young lady have worn a straw hat often?
Was it popular?
Well, we wore hats.
Yeah, we did.
And is that your pet dog?
That's Bill.
I was dating a boy named Bill at that time, and when I got that little puppy, I just named him Bill.
And I brought, it seems to me like I brought Bill to Norman with me.
And he lived there in the house and around the house?
Oh, yeah.
I always had a dog, and nearly always a Spitz dog.
I don't know how that happened.
Did the dogs play around on the campus?
I think so.
That's the porch to the house.
I think the steps are right close around here somewhere.
While your dad was president of A&M, what were his greatest concerns?
What was he hoping...
to do at A&M?
Well, I hardly know how to answer that.
He was just great on getting everybody educated.
He was... Did he have any pet subjects that he liked better than others?
Well, after he retired,
He taught a course in sociology, I think, and he enjoyed doing that.
He would have been a good teacher.
But, like, did he favor agriculture, or did he favor engineering?
Well, where's Ralph?
Where is that book that he wrote on agriculture?
He's...
And the top one, The Green Rising, is the book on agricultural economics.
Yes, yes.
So your dad then, his agriculture would have been his background.
Were there any worries that he had about A&M being changed by somebody else?
Were there any crises over?
Not that I recall.
As the First World War comes along, how did that affect A&M?
Well, I believe, if I remember correctly, that they offered the country, you know, the government,
the chance to use all the facilities down there I think they did for training and and it was it made a name for itself during the war.
Did a lot of the of the students go away like we saw in World War II?
The enrollment gets smaller?
I just can't answer things like that because I just don't remember that.
As you were getting ready to finish high school, were there World War II veterans coming back to the campus?
That I don't know either.
Let's see, some students that were very special
to A&M and to the state of Texas and beyond that were there just about the time you took your first year of A&M study.
One was M.T.
Harrington, who graduated in the spring of 22.
Do you remember him?
That was this book right here.
He would be in that book.
See, that's my brother's year, too.
And, yes, I remember him.
Can you tell me what you recall about him?
I can't.
I just remember mainly for his name, but that is a familiar name.
He was from Plano and would later become a great chemistry teacher, president, and chancellor.
His widow is still living, and she and Joe are in the same PEO chapter.
Oh, is that right?
Well, good, huh?
Let's see.
Do you remember a man named, a year before Dr. Harrington, H.B.
Zachary from San Antonio?
No.
Well, Uvalde then, but then Santa.
I don't believe I remember.
He would create one of the huge engineering construction, highway construction firms.
And his son is still running it today.
Then a character, a beloved artist named Buck Shewitz.
Oh, boy, I was hoping you...
Because in the yearbook, they describe him as the Curio from Cuero.
No, I don't recall him at all.
Then the last one would be Sterling Evans.
Mr. Evans is 100 years old.
It was last August, and I interviewed him, and he was a key influence at the time of coeducation, non-compulsory core, and so forth.
Was there any argument about making major changes at A&M to admit women?
The only thing that I can remember about admitting women was I just thought it was the worst idea I'd ever heard in my life.
It was going to ruin the school and all that I'd ever known about it.
I was letting people do like it.
That was your opinion?
That was my opinion.
But you attended there two years.
I know.
I know.
And you liked it.
I sure did.
But I felt like it was just going to delude all the military.
And the military to me, all the, everything about the military, the uniforms and the
the polished boots and the shiny ornaments and the way they kept everything.
And every afternoon at dinner time, the retreat.
You know, I've got all this in my mind that's not like yours at all.
Because there was this big, long military drive, they call it.
Went from Speza Hall down to Guyon Hall.
And that whole area would be, each company would have its own captain and all the officers lined up every evening.
And people would come in their cars just to watch retreat.
And they'd lower the flag and Star Spangled Banner
And you know, it was all impressive, and then giving all the orders, and they all marched into the mess hall.
And that just, all just appealed to me.
I loved every bit of that.
Did a young lady like you ever go out there and watch that retreat?
Well, I saw it every day, because it was so close to our house.
Did you and your family eat in the dining hall very often?
In Sabisa Dining Hall?
No.
Did you know Mr. Sabisa?
Yes.
Please tell us all you can remember about him.
I can't do that.
I can't do that because it's not all good.
Oh, really?
That I remember.
Well, tell us what you can that's good.
Well, I'll tell you what it was good that he did.
And that was on Sunday nights.
They would bake this bread that was just that homemade bread out of this wonderful.
And then he would slice it down the middle, take out some of the inside and fill it with broiled oysters and put the top down and bring it over for our Sunday supper.
Not all the time, you know, just every now and then.
And it was just wonderful.
So I remember, that is the good thing I remember about Mr. Spears.
Describe him physically.
Was he a big man, a little man?
No, he was kind of a little man.
He had a little white goatee.
Did he sound Germanic?
Did he seem to have a German accent still?
I think he had an accent.
Because as I recall, he had been on the...
the chef staff for the emperor of Austria-Hungary before coming to the United States.
I'm not surprised, yeah.
Was he stern?
No.
I don't know.
He just wasn't.
All right.
Back to Dean Kyle.
Describe him physically.
Well, he was tall and slender.
Pleasant?
Yeah, yeah.
She was too.
Now, were the Kyles, did your family and the Kyles, were those the closest friends?
They tried not to have the closest friends with the faculty people.
I mean, they didn't want to pick stuff.
They just liked them all.
And of course, my mother and father had these faculty receptions and had everybody.
But they didn't have this real close intimate friends.
They tried not to.
They would pick and choose, but now that I say that, I think that's the way my mother felt.
There was, I don't know, one of her good friends there was Ms. Youngblood.
Her husband was on faculty.
And, you know, the Waltons, you mentioned their name.
I've just been thinking about the Waltons because they were
Do you know anything about the Waltons from Texas A&M?
Why don't you sit up, and then we've got to get you propped up.
Oh, I'm doing fine.
Are you OK?
Yeah.
Yeah.
Reminisce about the Waltons, please.
Well, they had a daughter, Ethel Walton, and she was a contemporary of mine.
She was there on the campus.
I don't know whether she ever went to school there any night.
I don't remember that.
When your father wanted to relax, what did he do for fun, relaxation?
Got himself a book and sat down and read.
He read all the time.
What were his favorite books?
uh topics to read about oh was it fiction or no no not much fiction he had a very large library and among his other books he had a i think it was 600 volumes
Bible collection that he had bought all over Europe.
And the library down at Norman is named for him, Brazil Memorial Library.
And they have a nice room there.
The family donated the collection.
Oh, how nice.
But all through the years, he collected those.
He had some very rare, rare Bibles.
